creasingly isolated spheres. The roads were the product of a new form of government, the infrastructure state, marked by the unprecedented control bureaucrats wielded over decisions relating to everyday life.Does information really work to unite strangers? Do markets unite nations and peoples in common interests? There are lessons here for all who would end poverty or design their markets around the principle of participation. Guldi draws direct connections between traditional infrastructure and the contemporary collapse of the American Rust Belt, the decline of American infrastructure, the digital divide, and net neutrality. In the modern world, infrastructure is our principal tool for forging new communities, but it cannot outlast the control of governance by visionaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aInfrastructure (Economics)zGreat Britain. 0aRoadsxGovernment policyzGreat Britain. 0aTransportation and statezGreat Britain. 7aTechnology & Engineering / Civil / Transportation.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2012z9783110288995oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE MATHEMATICS, PHYSICS, ENGINEERING 2012z9783110293722oZDB-23-DMI08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PAKET MATHEMATIK, PHYSIK, INGENIEURWISS. 2012z9783110288926oZDB-23-DMP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067406288740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674062887423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674062887.jpg  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Packag